Diagnostic sanity check (mobilenet, 1 thread, 1 loop, shape=[224,224,3]):
  CPU (gpu=-1): min=12.89 max=12.89 avg=12.89 ms
  GPU (gpu=0):  min=12.89 max=12.89 avg=12.89 ms
  --> bit-for-bit identical timings; no Vulkan init log ever printed; no
      "[0 Mali-G78]" device enumeration line that a Vulkan-enabled benchncnn
      would emit on startup. Conclusion: Vulkan is NOT compiled in; gpu=0
      is silently falling back to the CPU path (benchncnn does not error
      out — it just runs on CPU when the Vulkan backend is absent).

Verdict:
  Vulkan is NOT compiled into this benchncnn build. No error line is printed
  (that's ncnn's behaviour when built without NCNN_VULKAN=ON — the gpu=0
  argument is accepted but quietly ignored, and execution falls through to
  the CPU backend, which is why all three successful model pairs show
  near-identical timings with noise-level deltas (+/- <10%, within run-to-run
  variance). The `strings` dump shows only metadata symbols
  (support_vulkan, use_vulkan_compute) baked into the ncnn::Net class; the
  actual Vulkan layer kernels and vkInstance bring-up are absent. To get
  real Mali-G78 GPU numbers we must cross-build ncnn for arm64-v8a Android
  with -DNCNN_VULKAN=ON (and ship libvulkan.so via the NDK), then re-run
  this sweep. No model sees >=1.5x speedup because no model is actually
  running on the GPU.
